in the positive octant of the S, u1, u2-space, which will be denoted by u∗ = (λ, ξ1, ξ2). Hence u∗ ∈ LK . It is easy to see that the trivial equilibria (0, 0, 0) and (K , 0, 0) are unstable provided 0 < λ < K (see [10] for details). It is clear
that all equilibria on LK are stable for all K that satisfy the inequality λ < K ≤ a2 + 2λ. This means that if food is scarce both
the r and k-strategists may live together in the long run in a steady state that depends on the initial values of the species. When
a2 + 2λ < K < a1 + 2λ (i.e., when a1 > a2) the family of equilibria on the line LK undergoes a split and a part of LK is unstable; that is, there exists a point (λ, ξ1(K ), ξ2(K )) on LK such that the equilibria on

LU = {(λ, ξ1, ξ2) ∈ LK : ξ1 < ξ1(K )}

are unstable for the flow of (13) and the equilibria on

LS = {(λ, ξ1, ξ2) ∈ LK : ξ1 > ξ1(K )}

are stable. The point (ξ1(K ), ξ2(K )) is obtained by solving the system

