G(u) = γ (1 − K )S − m1 a1 + S u1 − m2 a2 + S u2, m1 a2 + S u1 − d1u1, m2 a2 + S u2 − d2u2

and k(u) = (kij(u))3×3 is a 3 × 3 matrix. In general ([3], p. 300), the diffusion coefficients may be positive, negative or zero. In the
present model, we assume that these coefficients kij(u) satisfy

k11, k22, k33 > 0, k12, k13 ≥ 0 and k21, k23, k31, k32 ≤ 0.

(7)

The variables and parameters in (4) have the same meaning as in the model (1).
In the model (4), J0 = −k11(u)∇S − k12(u)∇u1 − k13(u)∇u2, J1 = −k21(u)∇S − k22(u)∇u1 − k23(u)∇u2 and J2 = −k31(u)∇S − k32(u)∇u1 − k33(u)∇u2 indicate the population fluxes of S, u1 and u2, respectively, where the terms k11(u), k22(u) and k33(u) represent the ‘‘self-diffusion’’ while the terms kij(u), i ̸= j, correspond to the ‘‘cross-diffusion’’.
The conditions k1j(u) ≥ 0, j = 2, 3, imply that the part −k12(u)∇u1 − k13(u)∇u2 of the flux of S is directed towards decreasing population density of uj, that is, the prey S runs away from the predators. On the other hand, the conditions k2j(u) ≤ 0, j = 1, 3, imply that the part −k21(u)∇S − k23(u)∇u2 of the flux of u1 is directed towards the increasing population density of S and u2, which means
that the predator u1 moves in anticipation of the predator u2 and of the defense switching behavior of the prey S, that is, u1 chases
the prey. Analogously, the conditions k3j(u) ≤ 0, j = 1, 2, imply that the part −k31(u)∇S − k32(u)∇u1 of the flux of u2 is directed
towards increasing population density of S and u1, which means that the predator u2 moves in anticipation of the predator u1 and of the defense switching behavior of the prey S, that is, u2 chases the prey. A more detailed discussion may be found in [3,21]. Thus, in order to discuss the diffusion-driven instability considering the strategy adopted by the predators taking advantage of the defense

