It follows from the linearization principle that a ‘non-trivial’ homogeneous solution of (11) is asymptotically stable if the eigenvalues

of the matrix Gu(u∗) − µjK (u∗) have negative real parts; if there exists a k ≥ 1 such that Gu(u∗) − µjK (u∗) has an eigenvalue with positive real part then the solution is unstable. Note that for µ0 = 0 the matrix Gu(u∗) has zero as an eigenvalue of multiplicity 1 and

