Theorem 1 may be viewed as a result on the preservation of stability under self-diffusion for prey population and cross-diffusion
for both predator populations for Model I. As a consequence, if λ < K < a2 + 2λ, the line of equilibrium points LK of (1) is locally asymptotically stable for the flow of (11). If K > a1 + 2λ, then LK is unstable. We have the following corollary.

Corollary 1. For any K satisfying a2 + 2λ ≤ K ≤ a1 + 2λ, the point (λ, ξ1(K ), ξ2(K )) splits LK in two parts LuK and LsK ; the equilibria of (11)
on the set
LuK = {(λ, ξ1, ξ2) ∈ LK : ξ1 < ξ1(K )}
are unstable and those on the set
LsK = {(λ, ξ1, ξ2) ∈ LK : ξ1 > ξ1(K )}
are stable, regardless the cross-diffusion coefficients given in the system (11).

Remark 3. The result in Corollary 1 shows that the zip bifurcation phenomenon is sustainable even by the introduction of cross-diffusion in the model (1). In the following, we present an example to illustrate the result obtained in Theorem 1.

