Thus, if u∗ is stable for the flow of (1) u∗ will be stable for the flow of (12) provided the inequality (22) holds for all j = 1, 2, . . .. Further, the equilibrium u∗ is unstable for the flow of (12), if any of the inequalities (23) or (24) holds for some j = 1, 2, . . .. □
In Theorem 2 we observe that the stability of the equilibria for Model II is not preserved as in the case of Model I (Theorem 1), which may be due to the introduction of cross-diffusion in all interacting populations.

Corollary 2. Suppose that u∗ is an equilibrium of (12) independent of x. Moreover, suppose that one of the conditions (23)–(24) holds. Then If u∗ is stable for the flow of (1), u∗ may not be stable for the flow of (12).

Remark 4. This final result shows that the Turing instability may emerge upon the introduction of cross-diffusion in the model (1) and the zip bifurcation phenomenon may not sustain.
